It looks like we have some duplicated information, probably from a merge between different datasets. For example, id, ID, and IATA all seem to refer to the International Air Transport Association (IATA) 3-letter airport codes. Let’s check the number of times those columns match:

summary <- airports %>% group_by(id) %>% summarize(across(c('ID','IATA'), n_distinct))
summary

The first summary table shows the number of unique values of ID and IATA for each value of id. The second summary table finds the maximum number of unique values. Since the maximum number is 1, we can be confident that the id, ID, and IATA columns always match.

Since id and ID have 0 missing values, but IATA has 750 NAs, there are some airports contained in the dataset(s) that used id / ID which are missing from the dataset that used IATA. Let’s keep the id column to preserve these airports, and explore what the rows with missing IATA are like.

Based on the filter we used, it seems that the airportID:source columns (all columns from airportID to source) came from a different data set, and the airports with missing values from IATA are just absent from this second dataset (because all other columns in airportID:source for these rows are also NA).

To be consistent with which latitude and longitude we use across the airports in our dataset, let’s stick with the ones that came from the first dataset, and drop the ones from the second dataset (longitude.y and latitude.y).

Finally, since we are only really interested in the graph of flight routes, where nodes are departure/destination airports and arcs are (directed) routes operated by airlines between airports, we don’t need a lot of the extra detail like the ICAO code, time zone, altitude, etc.

So country cannot refer to the country of the departure or arrival airport, since the same airport code has multiple unique values of country. It seems that country is then related to airline, since each airline has only a handful of values for country, and most airlines have only 1 country:

mult_airlines <- routes %>% group_by(airline) %>% summarize(countries = n_distinct(country)) %>% filter(countries > 2) %>% .$airline

It looks like some two-letter airline codes are repeated, perhaps because airlines registered in different countries are allowed to have the same code, or maybe some older airlines with routes in the data have since gone out of business or changed codes with another airline. Again, since we only really care about which airport pairs are served by any airline, and especially considering that only 22 of the 568 airlines are registered to more than 1 country, I’m not concerned about this data issue.

arcs <- routes %>% select(Source, Target)
glimpse(arcs)

The last step counts the number of times the unique airport pair occurs in the routes data. Since the data is directed, each one-way flight between two airports would be listed, i.e. \(AAA \rightarrow BBB\) and \(BBB \rightarrow AAA\) would be listed separately.

  1. Combine the nodelist and edgelist into a directed graph using graph_from_data_frame
g <- graph_from_data_frame(arcs)
  1. Plot the graph using plot.
plot(g, edge.arrow.size=0.2, vertex.size=1, vertex.label.cex=0.4, edge.width = E(g)$weight, vertex.label.family='Helvetica', layout=layout_with_lgl)
## Warning in text.default(x, y, labels = labels, col = label.color, family =
## label.family, : font family not found in Windows font database

V(g)$latitude <- airports$latitude[match(V(g)$name, airports$id)]
V(g)$longitude <- airports$longitude[match(V(g)$name, airports$id)]

latlong = matrix(c(V(g)$longitude, V(g)$latitude), ncol=2)
plot(g, edge.arrow.size=0.05, vertex.size=1, vertex.label=NA, edge.width = 0.1*E(g)$weight, vertex.label.family='Arial', layout=latlong, rescale=FALSE, asp=0, xlim=range(V(g)$longitude), ylim=range(V(g)$latitude))

library(tidyverse)
world <- map_data("world")

coords <- nodes %>% select(id:longitude)
el <- as_edgelist(g) %>% as_tibble

Adding Network Measures

  1. Compute in-degree, out-degree, and total degree for each node using degree and save each of them as node attributes. Call them in.deg, out.deg, and deg.

  2. Create a node attribute called size, and set it to the in-degree values of each node

  3. Assign colors to node attributes based on sex. Hint: Vertices operate like data rows, and can be selected using boolean conditions inside [ ]. R will understand common colors provided in as strings (e.g. R understand what “light blue” is).

  4. Replot data using the new variables to specify vertex size and color. Scale the size by 20.

Filtering Networks

  1. Filter portions of the main Demo_g graph based on sex using induced.subgraph

  2. Filter portions of the main graph Demo_g based on in-degree using induced.subgraph. Choose nodes with more than 2 connections towards them.

  3. Filter portions of the main graph Demo_g based on edge attributes using subgraph.edges. Choose relationships in year 2. Count the number of nodes and number of edges using vcount and ecount. Replot using graph attributes in part 8.
